<subSubSection id="0CF865053247FF8FFF4CFAF9FD54E789" pageId="15" pageNumber="497" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="445D368E3247FF8FFF4CFAF9FD54E789" blockId="15.[151,1437,150,249]" pageId="15" pageNumber="497">
<emphasis id="7696EA9C3247FF8FFF4CFAF9FE72E7C1" bold="true" box="[199,422,150,176]" pageId="15" pageNumber="497">Derivatio nominis.</emphasis>
The epithet of the name refers to the striking yellow colouration of the species: flavus = yellow (adjective) in Latin. The suffix - 
<emphasis id="7696EA9C3247FF8FFDC4FAD4FD43E7A5" box="[591,663,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="497">issimu</emphasis>
s (resp. - 
<emphasis id="7696EA9C3247FF8FFD7CFAD4FC87E7A5" box="[759,851,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="497">issimum</emphasis>
as neuter) is added to form its superlative grade as it is the most yellow species of this subgenus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
